# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: histogram-density
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] In statistics, **probability density estimation** or simply **density estimation** is the construction of an estimate, based on observed data, of an unobservable underlying probability density function.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] The unobservable density function is thought of as the density according to which a large population is distributed; the data are usually thought of as a random sample from that population.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] A variety of approaches to density estimation are used, including Parzen windows and a range of data clustering techniques, including vector quantization.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] The most basic form of density estimation is a rescaled histogram.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] We will consider records of the incidence of diabetes.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] The data were collected by the US National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] In this example, we construct three density estimates for "glu" (plasma glucose concentration), one conditional on the presence of diabetes, the second conditional on the absence of diabetes, and the third not conditional on diabetes.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] The conditional density estimates are then used to construct the probability of diabetes conditional on "glu".
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] The "glu" data were obtained from the MASS package of the R programming language.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] Within R, `?Pima.tr` and `?Pima.te` give a fuller account of the data.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] The mean of "glu" in the diabetes cases is 143.1 and the standard deviation is 31.26.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] The mean of "glu" in the non-diabetes cases is 110.0 and the standard deviation is 24.29.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] From this we see that, in this data set, diabetes cases are associated with greater levels of "glu".
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] This will be made clearer by plots of the estimated density functions.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] The first figure shows density estimates of *p*(glu | diabetes=1), *p*(glu | diabetes=0), and *p*(glu).
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] The density estimates are kernel density estimates using a Gaussian kernel.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] That is, a Gaussian density function is placed at each data point, and the sum of the density functions is computed over the range of the data.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] From the density of "glu" conditional on diabetes, we can obtain the probability of diabetes conditional on "glu" via Bayes' rule.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] For brevity, "diabetes" is abbreviated "db." in this formula.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] The second figure shows the estimated posterior probability *p*(diabetes=1 | glu).
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] From these data, it appears that an increased level of "glu" is associated with diabetes.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] A very natural use of density estimates is in the informal investigation of the properties of a given set of data.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] Density estimates can give a valuable indication of such features as skewness and multimodality in the data.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] In some cases they will yield conclusions that may then be regarded as self-evidently true, while in others all they will do is to point the way to further analysis and/or data collection.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] An important aspect of statistics is often the presentation of data back to the client in order to provide explanation and illustration of conclusions that may possibly have been obtained by other means.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] Density estimates are ideal for this purpose, for the simple reason that they are fairly easily comprehensible to non-mathematicians.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] More examples illustrating the use of density estimates for exploratory and presentational purposes, including the important case of bivariate data.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] Density estimation is also frequently used in anomaly detection or novelty detection: if an observation lies in a very low-density region, it is likely to be an anomaly or a novelty.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] In statistics, kernel density estimation (KDE) is the application of kernel smoothing for probability density estimation, i.e., a non-parametric method to estimate the probability density function of a random variable based on *kernels* as weights.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] KDE answers a fundamental data smoothing problem where inferences about the population are made based on a finite data sample.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] In some fields such as signal processing and econometrics it is also termed the Parzen–Rosenblatt window method, after Emanuel Parzen and Murray Rosenblatt, who are usually credited with independently creating it in its current form.
[src:histogram-density/density-estimation] One of the famous applications of kernel density estimation is in estimating the class-conditional marginal densities of data when using a naive Bayes classifier, which can improve its prediction accuracy.
[src:histogram-density/empirical-distribution-function] drawn from that distribution, and the horizontal steps of the blue step function (including the leftmost point in each step but not including the rightmost point) form the empirical distribution function of that sample.
[src:histogram-density/empirical-distribution-function] In statistics, an **empirical distribution function** (a.k.a. an **empirical cumulative distribution function**, **eCDF**) is the distribution function associated with the empirical measure of a sample.
[src:histogram-density/empirical-distribution-function] This cumulative distribution function is a step function that jumps up by 1/*n* at each of the *n* data points.
[src:histogram-density/empirical-distribution-function] Its value at any specified value of the measured variable is the fraction of observations of the measured variable that are less than or equal to the specified value.
[src:histogram-density/empirical-distribution-function] The empirical distribution function is an estimate of the cumulative distribution function that generated the points in the sample.
[src:histogram-density/empirical-distribution-function] It converges with probability 1 to that underlying distribution, according to the Glivenko–Cantelli theorem.
[src:histogram-density/empirical-distribution-function] A number of results exist to quantify the rate of convergence of the empirical distribution function to the underlying cumulative distribution function.
[src:histogram-density/empirical-distribution-function] A simple empirical estimate is the frequency distribution.
[src:histogram-density/empirical-distribution-function] Let (*X*1, …, *X**n*) be independent, identically distributed real random variables with the common cumulative distribution function *F*(*t*).
[src:histogram-density/empirical-distribution-function] For a fixed *t*, the indicator $\mathbf {1} _{X_{i}\leq t}$ is a Bernoulli random variable with parameter *p* = *F*(*t*); hence $n{\widehat {F}}_{n}(t)$ is a binomial random variable with mean *nF*(*t*) and variance *nF*(*t*)(1 − *F*(*t*)).
[src:histogram-density/empirical-distribution-function] This implies that ${\widehat {F}}_{n}(t)$ is an unbiased estimator for *F*(*t*).
[src:histogram-density/empirical-distribution-function] In some textbooks, the empirical distribution function is defined as ${\widehat {F}}_{n}(t)={\frac {1}{n+1}}\sum _{i=1}^{n}\mathbf {1} _{X_{i}\leq t}$ However, since the ratio (*n* + 1)/*n* approaches 1 as *n* goes to infinity, the asymptotic properties of the two definitions are the same.
[src:histogram-density/empirical-distribution-function] By the strong law of large numbers, the estimator ${\widehat {F}}_{n}(t)$ converges to *F*(*t*) as *n* → ∞ almost surely, for every value of *t*: ${\widehat {F}}_{n}(t)\ {\xrightarrow {\text{a.s.}}}\ F(t);$ thus the estimator ${\widehat {F}}_{n}(t)$ is consistent.
[src:histogram-density/empirical-distribution-function] This expression asserts the pointwise convergence of the empirical distribution function to the true cumulative distribution function.
[src:histogram-density/empirical-distribution-function] Other norm functions may be reasonably used here instead of the sup-norm.
[src:histogram-density/empirical-distribution-function] For example, the L2-norm gives rise to the Cramér–von Mises statistic.
[src:histogram-density/empirical-distribution-function] The asymptotic distribution can be further characterized in several different ways.
[src:histogram-density/empirical-distribution-function] Alternatively, the rate of convergence of ${\sqrt {n}}({\widehat {F}}_{n}-F)$ can also be quantified in terms of the asymptotic behavior of the sup-norm of this expression.
[src:histogram-density/empirical-distribution-function] As per the above bounds, we can plot the Empirical CDF, CDF and confidence intervals for different distributions by using any one of the statistical implementations.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] A **histogram** is a visual representation of the distribution of quantitative data.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] To construct a histogram, the first step is to "bin" (or "bucket") the range of values— divide the entire range of values into a series of intervals—and then count how many values fall into each interval.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] The bins are usually specified as consecutive, non-overlapping intervals of a variable.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] The bins (intervals) are adjacent and are typically (but not required to be) of equal size.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Histograms give a rough sense of the density of the underlying distribution of the data, and often for density estimation: estimating the probability density function of the underlying variable.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] The total area of a histogram used for probability density is always normalized to 1.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] If the length of the intervals on the *x*-axis are all 1, then a histogram is identical to a relative frequency plot.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Histograms are sometimes confused with bar charts.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] In a histogram, each bin is for a different range of values, so altogether the histogram illustrates the distribution of values.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] But in a bar chart, each bar is for a different category of observations (e.g., each bar might be for a different population), so altogether the bar chart can be used to compare different categories.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Some authors recommend that bar charts always have gaps between the bars to clarify that they are not histograms.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] The term *histogram* was first introduced by Karl Pearson, the founder of mathematical statistics, in lectures delivered in 1892 at University College London.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Pearson's term is sometimes incorrectly said to combine the Greek root γραμμα (*gramma*; 'figure' or 'drawing') with the root ἱστορία (historia; 'inquiry or 'history').
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Alternatively the root ἱστίον (*histion*) is also proposed, meaning 'web' or 'tissue' (as in histology, the study of biological tissue).
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Both of these etymologies are incorrect, and in fact Pearson, who knew Ancient Greek well, derived the term from a different if homophonous Greek root, ἱστός ('something set upright' or 'mast'), referring to the vertical bars in the graph.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Pearson's new term was embedded in a series of other analogous neologisms, such as *stigmogram* and *radiogram*.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Pearson himself noted in 1895 that, although the term *histogram* was new, the type of graph it designates was "a common form of graphical representation".
[src:histogram-density/histogram] In fact the technique of using a bar graph to represent statistical measurements was devised by the Scottish economist, William Playfair, in his *Commercial and political atlas* (1786).
[src:histogram-density/histogram] The words used to describe the patterns in a histogram are: "symmetric", "skewed left" or "right", "unimodal", "bimodal" or "multimodal".
[src:histogram-density/histogram] It is a good idea to plot the data using several different bin widths to learn more about it.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Here is an example on tips given in a restaurant.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Census Bureau found that there were 124 million people who work outside of their homes.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Using their data on the time occupied by travel to work, the table below shows the absolute number of people who responded with travel times "at least 30 but less than 35 minutes" is higher than the numbers for the categories above and below it.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] This is likely due to people rounding their reported journey time.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] The problem of reporting values as somewhat arbitrarily rounded numbers is a common phenomenon when collecting data from people.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] This histogram shows the number of cases per unit interval as the height of each block, so that the area of each block is equal to the number of people in the survey who fall into its category.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] The area under the curve represents the total number of cases (124 million).
[src:histogram-density/histogram] This type of histogram shows absolute numbers, with Q in thousands.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] This histogram differs from the first only in the vertical scale.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] The area of each block is the fraction of the total that each category represents, and the total area of all the bars is equal to 1 (the fraction meaning "all").
[src:histogram-density/histogram] The curve displayed is a simple density estimate.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] This version shows proportions, and is also known as a unit area histogram.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] In other words, a histogram represents a frequency distribution by means of rectangles whose widths represent class intervals and whose areas are proportional to the corresponding frequencies: the height of each is the average frequency density for the interval.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] The intervals are placed together in order to show that the data represented by the histogram, while exclusive, is also contiguous.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] (E.g., in a histogram it is possible to have two connecting intervals of 10.5–20.5 and 20.5–33.5, but not two connecting intervals of 10.5–20.5 and 22.5–32.5.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] The data used to construct a histogram are generated via a function *m**i* that counts the number of observations that fall into each of the disjoint categories (known as *bins*).
[src:histogram-density/histogram] A histogram can be thought of as a simplistic kernel density estimation, which uses a kernel to smooth frequencies over the bins.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] This yields a smoother probability density function, which will in general more accurately reflect distribution of the underlying variable.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] The density estimate could be plotted as an alternative to the histogram, and is usually drawn as a curve rather than a set of boxes.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Histograms are nevertheless preferred in applications, when their statistical properties need to be modeled.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] The correlated variation of a kernel density estimate is very difficult to describe mathematically, while it is simple for a histogram where each bin varies independently.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] An alternative to kernel density estimation is the average shifted histogram, which is fast to compute and gives a smooth curve estimate of the density without using kernels.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] A cumulative histogram: a mapping that counts the cumulative number of observations in all of the bins up to the specified bin.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] There is no "best" number of bins, and different bin sizes can reveal different features of the data.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Grouping data is at least as old as Graunt's work in the 17th century, but no systematic guidelines were given until Sturges's work in 1926.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Using wider bins where the density of the underlying data points is low reduces noise due to sampling randomness; using narrower bins where the density is high (so the signal drowns the noise) gives greater precision to the density estimation.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Thus varying the bin-width within a histogram can be beneficial.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Nonetheless, equal-width bins are widely used.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Some theoreticians have attempted to determine an optimal number of bins, but these methods generally make strong assumptions about the shape of the distribution.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Depending on the actual data distribution and the goals of the analysis, different bin widths may be appropriate, so experimentation is usually needed to determine an appropriate width.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] There are, however, various useful guidelines and rules of thumb.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] The braces indicate the ceiling function.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] which takes the square root of the number of data points in the sample and rounds to the next integer.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] This rule is suggested by a number of elementary statistics textbooks and widely implemented in many software packages.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Sturges's rule is derived from a binomial distribution and implicitly assumes an approximately normal distribution.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Sturges's formula implicitly bases bin sizes on the range of the data, and can perform poorly if *n* < 30, because the number of bins will be small—less than seven—and unlikely to show trends in the data well.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] On the other extreme, Sturges's formula may overestimate bin width for very large datasets, resulting in oversmoothed histograms.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] It may also perform poorly if the data are not normally distributed.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] When compared to Scott's rule and the Terrell-Scott rule, two other widely accepted formulas for histogram bins, the output of Sturges's formula is closest when *n* ≈ 100.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] The Rice rule is presented as a simple alternative to Sturges's rule.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Doane's formula is a modification of Sturges's formula which attempts to improve its performance with non-normal data.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] where ${\hat {\sigma }}$ is the sample standard deviation.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Scott's normal reference rule is optimal for random samples of normally distributed data, in the sense that it minimizes the integrated mean squared error of the density estimate.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] This is the default rule used in Microsoft Excel.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] The Terrell–Scott rule is not a normal reference rule.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] It gives the minimum number of bins required for an asymptotically optimal histogram, where optimality is measured by the integrated mean squared error.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] The bound is derived by finding the 'smoothest' possible density, which turns out to be ${\frac {3}{4}}(1-x^{2})$ .
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Any other density will require more bins, hence the above estimate is also referred to as the 'oversmoothed' rule.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] The similarity of the formulas and the fact that Terrell and Scott were at Rice University when the proposed it suggests that this is also the origin of the Rice rule.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] which is based on the interquartile range, denoted by IQR.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] It replaces 3.5σ of Scott's rule with 2 IQR, which is less sensitive than the standard deviation to outliers in data.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Here, $N_{k}$ is the number of datapoints in the *k*th bin, and choosing the value of *h* that minimizes *J* will minimize integrated mean squared error.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Rather than choosing evenly spaced bins, for some applications it is preferable to vary the bin width.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] A common case is to choose *equiprobable bins*, where the number of samples in each bin is expected to be approximately equal.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] The bins may be chosen according to some known distribution or may be chosen based on the data so that each bin has $\approx n/k$ samples.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] When plotting the histogram, the *frequency density* is used for the dependent axis.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] While all bins have approximately equal area, the heights of the histogram approximate the density distribution.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] This choice of bins is motivated by maximizing the power of a Pearson chi-squared test testing whether the bins do contain equal numbers of samples.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Where $\Phi ^{-1}$ is the probit function.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Following this rule for $\alpha =0.05$ would give between $1.88n^{2/5}$ and $3.77n^{2/5}$ ; the coefficient of 2 is chosen as an easy-to-remember value from this broad optimum.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] A good reason why the number of bins should be proportional to ${\sqrt[{3}]{n}}$ is the following: suppose that the data are obtained as n independent realizations of a bounded probability distribution with smooth density.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Then the histogram remains equally "rugged" as n tends to infinity.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] If s is the "width" of the distribution (e. g., the standard deviation or the inter-quartile range), then the number of units in a bin (the frequency) is of order $nh/s$ and the *relative* standard error is of order ${\sqrt {s/(nh)}}$ .
[src:histogram-density/histogram] Compared to the next bin, the relative change of the frequency is of order $h/s$ provided that the derivative of the density is non-zero.
[src:histogram-density/histogram] These two are of the same order if h is of order $s/{\sqrt[{3}]{n}}$ , so that k is of order ${\sqrt[{3}]{n}}$ .
[src:histogram-density/histogram] This simple cubic root choice can also be applied to bins with non-constant widths.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] In statistics, **kernel density estimation** (**KDE**) is the application of kernel smoothing for probability density estimation, i.e., a non-parametric method to estimate the probability density function of a random variable based on *kernels* as weights.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] In some fields such as signal processing and econometrics it is also termed the **Parzen–Rosenblatt window** method, after Emanuel Parzen and Murray Rosenblatt, who are usually credited with independently creating it in its current form.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] Let $\mathbf {x} =\left(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},...\right)$ be independent and identically distributed samples drawn from some univariate distribution with an unknown density *f* at any given point x.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] We are interested in estimating the shape of this function *f*.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] A kernel with subscript h is called the *scaled kernel* and defined as *K**h*(*x*) = ⁠1/*h*⁠ *K*(⁠*x*/*h*⁠).
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] Intuitively one wants to choose h as small as the data will allow; however, there is always a trade-off between the bias of the estimator and its variance.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] The choice of bandwidth is discussed in more detail below.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] A range of kernel functions are commonly used: uniform, triangular, biweight, triweight, Epanechnikov (parabolic), normal, and others.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] The Epanechnikov kernel is optimal in a mean square error sense, though the loss of efficiency is small for the kernels listed previously.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] Due to its convenient mathematical properties, the normal kernel is often used, which means *K*(*x*) = *ϕ*(*x*), where ϕ is the standard normal density function.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] The construction of a kernel density estimate finds interpretations in fields outside of density estimation.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] For example, in thermodynamics, this is equivalent to the amount of heat generated when heat kernels (the fundamental solution to the heat equation) are placed at each data point locations *xi*.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] Similar methods are used to construct discrete Laplace operators on point clouds for manifold learning (e.g. diffusion map).
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] Kernel density estimates are closely related to histograms, but can be endowed with properties such as smoothness or continuity by using a suitable kernel.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] For the histogram, first, the horizontal axis is divided into sub-intervals or bins which cover the range of the data: In this case, six bins each of width 2.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] Whenever a data point falls inside this interval, a box of height 1/12 is placed there.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] If more than one data point falls inside the same bin, the boxes are stacked on top of each other.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] For the kernel density estimate, normal kernels with a standard deviation of 1.5 (indicated by the red dashed lines) are placed on each of the data points *xi*.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] The kernels are summed to make the kernel density estimate (solid blue curve).
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] The smoothness of the kernel density estimate (compared to the discreteness of the histogram) illustrates how kernel density estimates converge faster to the true underlying density for continuous random variables.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] The bandwidth of the kernel is a free parameter which exhibits a strong influence on the resulting estimate.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] To illustrate its effect, we take a simulated random sample from the standard normal distribution (plotted at the blue spikes in the rug plot on the horizontal axis).
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] The grey curve is the true density (a normal density with mean 0 and variance 1).
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] In comparison, the red curve is *undersmoothed* since it contains too many spurious data artifacts arising from using a bandwidth *h* = 0.05, which is too small.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] The green curve is *oversmoothed* since using the bandwidth *h* = 2 obscures much of the underlying structure.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] The black curve with a bandwidth of *h* = 0.337 is considered to be optimally smoothed since its density estimate is close to the true density.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] An extreme situation is encountered in the limit $h\to 0$ (no smoothing), where the estimate is a sum of n delta functions centered at the coordinates of analyzed samples.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] In the other extreme limit $h\to \infty$ the estimate retains the shape of the used kernel, centered on the mean of the samples (completely smooth).
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] where *o* is the little o notation, and n the sample size (as above).
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] where ${\textstyle R(g)=\int g(x)^{2}\,dx}$ for a function *g*, ${\textstyle m_{2}(K)=\int x^{2}K(x)\,dx}$ and $f''$ is the second derivative of f and K is the kernel.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] Neither the AMISE nor the *h*AMISE formulas can be used directly since they involve the unknown density function f or its second derivative $f''$ .
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] To overcome that difficulty, a variety of automatic, data-based methods have been developed to select the bandwidth.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] Several review studies have been undertaken to compare their efficacies, with the general consensus that the plug-in selectors and cross validation selectors are the most useful over a wide range of data sets.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] Substituting any bandwidth h which has the same asymptotic order *n*−1/5 as *h*AMISE into the AMISE gives that AMISE(*h*) = *O*(*n*−4/5), where *O* is the big *O* notation.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] It can be shown that, under weak assumptions, there cannot exist a non-parametric estimator that converges at a faster rate than the kernel estimator.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] Note that the *n*−4/5 rate is slower than the typical *n*−1 convergence rate of parametric methods.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] If the bandwidth is not held fixed, but is varied depending upon the location of either the estimate (balloon estimator) or the samples (pointwise estimator), this produces a particularly powerful method termed adaptive or variable bandwidth kernel density estimation.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] Bandwidth selection for kernel density estimation of heavy-tailed distributions is relatively difficult.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] An h value is considered more robust when it improves the fit for long-tailed and skewed distributions or for bimodal mixture distributions.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] Another modification that will improve the model is to reduce the factor from 1.06 to 0.9.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] This approximation is termed the *normal distribution approximation*, Gaussian approximation, or *Silverman's rule of thumb*.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] While this rule of thumb is easy to compute, it should be used with caution as it can yield widely inaccurate estimates when the density is not close to being normal.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] The estimate based on the rule-of-thumb bandwidth is significantly oversmoothed.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] One difficulty with applying this inversion formula is that it leads to a diverging integral, since the estimate ${\hat {\varphi }}(t)$ is unreliable for large t's.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] To circumvent this problem, the estimator ${\hat {\varphi }}(t)$ is multiplied by a damping function *ψh*(*t*) = *ψ*(*ht*), which is equal to 1 at the origin and then falls to 0 at infinity.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] The "bandwidth parameter" h controls how fast we try to dampen the function ${\hat {\varphi }}(t)$ .
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] In particular when h is small, then *ψh*(*t*) will be approximately one for a large range of t's, which means that ${\hat {\varphi }}(t)$ remains practically unaltered in the most important region of t's.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] The most common choice for function *ψ* is either the uniform function *ψ*(*t*) = **1**{−1 ≤ *t* ≤ 1}, which effectively means truncating the interval of integration in the inversion formula to [−1/*h*, 1/*h*], or the Gaussian function *ψ*(*t*) = *e**−πt*2.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] where *K* is the Fourier transform of the damping function *ψ*.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] Thus the kernel density estimator coincides with the characteristic function density estimator.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] Namely, M is the collection of points for which the density function is locally maximized.
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] A natural estimator of M is a plug-in from KDE, where $g(x)$ and $\lambda _{1}(x)$ are KDE version of $g(x)$ and $\lambda _{1}(x)$ .
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] Under mild assumptions, $M_{c}$ is a consistent estimator of M .
[src:histogram-density/kernel-density-estimation] Note that one can use the mean shift algorithm to compute the estimator $M_{c}$ numerically.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Probability density is the probability per unit length, in other words.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] The (absolute) probability for a continuous random variable to take on any particular value is zero.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Therefore, the value of the PDF at two different samples can be used to infer, in any particular draw of the random variable, how much more likely it is that the random variable would be close to one point compared to the other.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] More precisely, the PDF is used to specify the probability of the random variable falling *within a particular range of values*, as opposed to taking on any one value.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] This probability is given by the integral of a continuous variable's PDF over that range, where the integral is the nonnegative area under the density function between the lowest and greatest values of the range.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] The PDF is nonnegative everywhere, and the area under the entire curve is equal to one, such that the probability of the random variable falling within the set of possible values is 100%.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] The terms *probability distribution function* and *probability function* can also denote the probability density function.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] However, this use is not standard among probabilists and statisticians.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] In other sources, "probability distribution function" may be used when the probability distribution is defined as a function over general sets of values or it may refer to the cumulative distribution function (CDF), or it may be a probability mass function (PMF) rather than the density.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] *Density function* itself is also used for the probability mass function, leading to further confusion.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] In general the PMF is used in the context of discrete random variables (random variables that take values on a countable set), while the PDF is used in the context of continuous random variables.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Both PMF and PDF are fundamental concepts in statistical inference.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Suppose bacteria of a certain species typically live 20 to 30 hours.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] The probability that a bacterium lives *exactly* 5 hours is equal to zero.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] A lot of bacteria live for approximately 5 hours, but there is no chance that any given bacterium dies at exactly 5.00... hours.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] However, the probability that the bacterium dies between 5 hours and 5.01 hours is quantifiable.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Then, the probability that the bacterium dies between 5 hours and 5.001 hours should be about 0.002, since this time interval is one-tenth as long as the previous.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] The probability that the bacterium dies between 5 hours and 5.0001 hours should be about 0.0002, and so on.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] In this example, the ratio (probability of dying during an interval) / (duration of the interval) is approximately constant, and equal to 2 per hour (or 2 hour−1).
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] For example, there is 0.02 probability of dying in the 0.01-hour interval between 5 and 5.01 hours, and (0.02 probability / 0.01 hours) = 2 hour−1.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] This quantity 2 hour−1 is called the probability density for dying at around 5 hours.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Therefore, the probability that the bacterium dies at 5 hours can be written as (2 hour−1) *dt*.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] This is the probability that the bacterium dies within an infinitesimal window of time around 5 hours, where *dt* is the duration of this window.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] For example, the probability that it lives longer than 5 hours, but shorter than (5 hours + 1 nanosecond), is (2 hour−1)×(1 nanosecond) ≈ 6×10−13 (using the unit conversion 3.6×1012 nanoseconds = 1 hour).
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] There is a probability density function *f* with *f*(5 hours) = 2 hour−1.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] The integral of *f* over any window of time (not only infinitesimal windows but also large windows) is the probability that the bacterium dies in that window.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] A probability density function is most commonly associated with absolutely continuous univariate distributions.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Intuitively, one can think of $f_{X}(x)\,dx$ as being the probability of X falling within the infinitesimal interval $[x,x+dx]$ .
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] In the continuous univariate case above, the reference measure is the Lebesgue measure.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] The probability mass function of a discrete random variable is the density with respect to the counting measure over the sample space (usually the set of integers, or some subset thereof).
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] It is not possible to define a density with reference to an arbitrary measure (e.g. one can not choose the counting measure as a reference for a continuous random variable).
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Furthermore, when it does exist, the density is almost unique, meaning that any two such densities coincide almost everywhere.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Unlike a probability, a probability density function can take on values greater than one; for example, the continuous uniform distribution on the interval [0, 1/2] has probability density *f*(*x*) = 2 for 0 ≤ *x* ≤ 1/2 and *f*(*x*) = 0 elsewhere.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Not every probability distribution has a density function: the distributions of discrete random variables do not; nor does the Cantor distribution, even though it has no discrete component, i.e., does not assign positive probability to any individual point.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] A distribution has a density function if its cumulative distribution function *F*(*x*) is absolutely continuous.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] If a probability distribution admits a density, then the probability of every one-point set {*a*} is zero; the same holds for finite and countable sets.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Two probability densities *f* and *g* represent the same probability distribution precisely if they differ only on a set of Lebesgue measure zero.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] In the field of statistical physics, a non-formal reformulation of the relation above between the derivative of the cumulative distribution function and the probability density function is generally used as the definition of the probability density function.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] It is possible to represent certain discrete random variables as well as random variables involving both a continuous and a discrete part with a generalized probability density function using the Dirac delta function.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] (This is not possible with a probability density function in the sense defined above, it may be done with a distribution.) For example, consider a binary discrete random variable having the Rademacher distribution—that is, taking −1 or 1 for values, with probability 1⁄2 each.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] This substantially unifies the treatment of discrete and continuous probability distributions.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] The above expression allows for determining statistical characteristics of such a discrete variable (such as the mean, variance, and kurtosis), starting from the formulas given for a continuous distribution of the probability.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] It is common for probability density functions (and probability mass functions) to be parametrized—that is, to be characterized by unspecified parameters.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] A given set of parameters describes a single distribution within the family sharing the functional form of the density.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] This normalization factor is outside the kernel of the distribution.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Since the parameters are constants, reparametrizing a density in terms of different parameters to give a characterization of a different random variable in the family, means simply substituting the new parameter values into the formula in place of the old ones.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] For continuous random variables *X*1, ..., *Xn*, it is also possible to define a probability density function associated to the set as a whole, often called **joint probability density function**.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] For *i* = 1, 2, ..., *n*, let *f**X**i*(*x**i*) be the probability density function associated with variable *Xi* alone.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] This elementary example illustrates the above definition of multidimensional probability density functions in the simple case of a function of a set of two variables.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] If the probability density function of a random variable (or vector) *X* is given as *fX*(*x*), it is possible (but often not necessary; see below) to calculate the probability density function of some variable *Y* = *g*(*X*).
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] This is also called a "change of variable" and is in practice used to generate a random variable of arbitrary shape *f**g*(*X*) = *fY* using a known (for instance, uniform) random number generator.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] It is tempting to think that in order to find the expected value E(*g*(*X*)), one must first find the probability density *f**g*(*X*) of the new random variable *Y* = *g*(*X*).
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] The values of the two integrals are the same in all cases in which both *X* and *g*(*X*) actually have probability density functions.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] It is not necessary that *g* be a one-to-one function.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] In some cases the latter integral is computed much more easily than the former.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] See Law of the unconscious statistician.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Here *g*−1 denotes the inverse function.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] This follows from the fact that the probability contained in a differential area must be invariant under change of variables.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] For functions that are not monotonic, the probability density function for y is $\sum _{k=1}^{n(y)}\left|{\frac {d}{dy}}g_{k}^{-1}(y)\right|\cdot f_{X}{\big (}g_{k}^{-1}(y){\big )},$ where *n*(*y*) is the number of solutions in x for the equation $g(x)=y$ , and $g_{k}^{-1}(y)$ are these solutions.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Suppose **x** is an n-dimensional random variable with joint density *f*.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Let $V:\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R}$ be a differentiable function and X be a random vector taking values in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , $f_{X}$ be the probability density function of X and $\delta (\cdot )$ be the Dirac delta function.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Let Z be a collapsed random variable with probability density function $p_{Z}(z)=\delta (z)$ (i.e., a constant equal to zero).
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Applying the change of variable theorem from the previous section we obtain that $f_{Y,X}(y,x)=f_{X}(\mathbf {x} )\delta {\big (}y-V(\mathbf {x} ){\big )},$ which if marginalized over x leads to the desired probability density function.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] This can be derived from a two-way change of variables involving *Y* = *U* + *V* and *Z* = *V*, similarly to the example below for the quotient of independent random variables.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Given two independent random variables *U* and *V*, each of which has a probability density function, the density of the product *Y* = *UV* and quotient *Y* = *U*/*V* can be computed by a change of variables.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Then, the joint density *p*(*y*,*z*) can be computed by a change of variables from *U*,*V* to *Y*,*Z*, and *Y* can be derived by marginalizing out *Z* from the joint density.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] This method crucially requires that the transformation from *U*,*V* to *Y*,*Z* be bijective.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] The above transformation meets this because *Z* can be mapped directly back to *V*, and for a given *V* the quotient *U*/*V* is monotonic.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] This is similarly the case for the sum *U* + *V*, difference *U* − *V* and product *UV*.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Exactly the same method can be used to compute the distribution of other functions of multiple independent random variables.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] Given two standard normal variables *U* and *V*, the quotient can be computed as follows.
[src:histogram-density/probability-density-function] This is the density of a standard Cauchy distribution.
[src:histogram-density/rug-plot] A **rug plot** is a plot of data for a single quantitative variable, displayed as marks along an axis.
[src:histogram-density/rug-plot] It is used to visualise the distribution of the data.
[src:histogram-density/rug-plot] As such it is analogous to a histogram with zero-width bins, or a one-dimensional scatter plot.
[src:histogram-density/rug-plot] Rug plots are often used in combination with two-dimensional scatter plots by placing a rug plot of the x values of the data along the x-axis, and similarly for the y values.
[src:histogram-density/rug-plot] This is the origin of the term "rug plot", as these rug plots with perpendicular markers look like tassels along the edges of the rectangular "rug" of the scatter plot.
